If you are using the Version 2 of the AWS SDK, the simplest way is to use the deserializer Amazon uses internally:

AWS Lambda Java Runtime Serialization

    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;com.amazonaws&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;aws-lambda-java-serialization&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;1.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

It works as follow:

    PojoSerializer&lt;S3Event&gt; s3EventSerializer = LambdaEventSerializers.serializerFor(S3Event.class, ClassLoader.getSystemClassLoader());
    S3Event event = s3EventSerializer.fromJson(inputStream);

----------------------------

**There is an important thing to know (AWS SDK Version 2 vs. Version 1)**:

If there is a problem with your JSON (incompatible field value or JodaTime library is not in the classpath), the serializer says nothing and activates the AWS SDK 1 fallback. At the end you will get an error like this:

    java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: com.amazonaws.services.s3.event.S3EventNotification$S3EventNotificationRecord.

This message is **wrong**. The AWS deserializer works perfectly with both Version 2 and Version 1. The library itself is not dependent on SDK (neither 1 nor 2). Most probably you need to check you JSON.

You could use the `EventLoader` class:

`S3Event s3Event  = EventLoader.loadS3Event(&quot;s3-event.json&quot;);`

Add this dependency to your project:
```xml
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;com.amazonaws&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;aws-lambda-java-tests&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;1.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```

More about this topic:
- https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/opensource/testing-aws-lambda-functions-written-in-java/
- http://diego-pacheco.blogspot.com/2021/04/testing-aws-lambdas-with-java.html

